english:
  title: Two Untitled Poems
  author: Lee Won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.

    Autumn fades in this lonely village,
    Wild geese cross the silver river.
    Laziness makes it hard to open books—
    With years declining, sleep eludes me.

    River winds blow the evening trumpet call,
    Night's moon trembles at the clear flute's song.
    To speak of you—I dare not venture words,
    Leaning on my pillow, befriending the lamplight.

    II.

    One lamp dims into darkness,
    And the solitary minister's tears flow still.
    The empty window receives the moon's full gaze,
    Thin robes—I do not refuse the cold.

    Wine exhausted, sorrow remains bitter,
    The night deepens, dreams begin to fade.
    I long for those I cherish, yet see them not—
    Turning back, I gaze toward the clouded hills.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'silver river' refers to the Milky Way, here representing the vast distance between the poet and the absent beloved.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'solitary minister' is a self-reference, expressing the poet's isolation and perhaps political or personal estrangement.
  - key: ''
    value: These poems employ the classical Buddhist and Daoist imagery of autumn and night to explore themes of loneliness, longing, and the passage of time.
